library(BIS620.2022.final)

1.Background and Motivation

Diabetes is a non-recoverable disease that requires lifelong treatment once diagnosed. Due to the long disease cycle, it is prone to recurrence and always needs patients to be readmitted to the hospital multiple times. However, frequent readmission can put significant pressure on healthcare resources, while it is also an important indicator that shows the quality of care provided by healthcare facilities. Based on that, it is essential to evaluate and predict the risk of readmission while exploring the factors contributing to it.

This project would focus on predicting which patient would be readmitted, with the diabetes data that represents the 10 years clinical care record for diabetic patients at 130 US hospitals. Taking it as the primary research question, this project would also conduct data cleaning, exploration and visualization, analyse the relationship between various factors and the readmission risk of diabetic patients, in order to better understand the data and give sensible prediction.



2. Data Description and cleaning

All of analysis would based on the diabetic patients readmission data. It has 66221 observations, 48 explanatory variables, also one response variable readmitted denotes whether the patient is readmitted to the hospital within 30 days. Since there are too many variables, please refer to Apendix for detailed variable description.

load the data from the package:

data("diabetic_data")
head(diabetic_data, 5)

Since the original data comes from the Health Facts database, there are a large number of token representations (e.g., adoption_type_id = 1 for emergency). Replacing these marks with its actual meaning with the corresponding mapping table provided by the database. Following function could be used for any similar id - description mapping.

data("ids_map")
diabetic_data <- data_ids_map(diabetic_data, ids_map)

also, there are three variables diag_1, diag_2, diag_3 refers to the ICD-9 coding, which has too much unique values (more than 800), try to map them with the primary category of the corresponding disease.

Similarly, following function in the package could be used for any ICD-9 mapping.

                             data_icd = icd9_map,

2.1 Data cleaning

First of all, as the data here has possible missing values, outlier and extreme imbalanced variables, try to do data cleaning before conducting analysis.


2.1.1 dealing with missing value

Noting the presence of a large number of symbols such as ? and unknown in the data, converting these marks to NA to mark missing values with the function replace_missing_dataset

# map NA
mark_list <- c("?", "unknown", "invalid", "not available", "not mapped",
              "null", "none")
diabetic_data <- replace_missing_dataset(diabetic_data, mark_list = mark_list)

diabetic_ori <- diabetic_data

explore the missing proportion and possible missing pattern with the function missing_explore, which would give missing_table to show the proportion and pattern_plot to show the missing pattern

# knitr::opts_chunk$set(fig.width=5, fig.height=4) 
res <- missing_explore(diabetic_data)
# show the missing proportion
res$missing_table
# show the missing pattern
plot(res$pattern_plot, oma = c(12, 3, 2, 2))


based on the result, 8 of 47 explanatory variables have missing value. Based on the plot above, there is no significant missing pattern (such as some variables are always missing together as a pair). Assume that there is no correlation between the missing value, i.e.missing at random (MAR).

There are some columns have too many missing values while some only has few observations missing.

considering:

  • dropping the columns with missing proportion >= 94%
  • dropping observations which is missing with variables that only have <=4% missing.
  • otherwise, as it is missing at random here, using a new level named other to fill the missing for factor variables while using median to fill for numerical columns.
res <- missing_explore(diabetic_data,
            is_drop = TRUE, upper_pro = 0.94, lower_pro = 0.04,
            is_fill = TRUE, fill_mark_fac = "others", fill_cre_num = "median")
#> [1] "auto_process done, with 4.167% columns deleted and 2.812% rows dropped"
diabetic_data <- res$newdata

based on the output, there are only 4% (2) columns and less than 3% rows are dropped, the loss of data is acceptable.


2.1.2 outlier exploration

Considering the relatively large number of variables, it is complicated to check the outlier one by one, so here giving a rough exploration of outlier with the following definition:

  • if an obs. is <= Q1-(1.5)IQR or >=Q3+(1.5)IQR, define it as away from the whole group
  • if one variable has only small amount of obs away from the whole group (e.g.1%), set these obs as the outliers for this variable.
diabetic_data <- outlier_explore(diabetic_data, outlier_prop = .01,
                                 is_drop = FALSE, is_plot = TRUE)

We could assume that these outliers are not recorded wrongly and should be considered reasonable. Set is_drop = FALSE and keep these observations.


2.1.3 drop the extreme imbalance columns

A variable is considered to be extremely imbalanced if, more than 98% of the observations are concentrated at a certain level. The extremely imbalanced variables are automatically checked and removed:

diabetic_data <- extreme_imbalance_col(diabetic_data, extreme_prop = .98,
                                 is_drop = TRUE, is_table = FALSE)

In summary, the basic data cleaning is finished. 64359 observations and 29 explanatory variables (with one response variables) are left.



2.2 Data Encoding with WOE

WOE (weight of evidence) is a supervised coding of the variables and is often used in financial risk models. After discretizing the data into bins, WOE values can be computed for each group to represent the difference between the proportion of the target customers in the current group to all target customers and the proportion of non-target customers in the current group to all non-target customers. In this project, readmitted patients are defined as target customers.

Let \(y_{i}\) denote the number of target customers in group \(i\) (i.e., the number of readmitted patients) and \(n_i\) denote the number of non-target customers in group \(i\) (i.e., the number of non-readmitted patients), \(y_T\), \(n_T\) denote the total number of target customers and non-target customers in data. The WOE value for group \(i\) at this point is calculated as follows: \[WOE_{i} = \ln{\frac{py_i}{pn_i}} = \ln{\frac{y_i/y_T}{n_i/n_T}}\]

First, considering the categorical variables in the data always have too many levels, it always leads to difficulties in modeling if treating them directly as dummy variables. WOE coding always implied with tree-based binning, it is a good way to combine some of the levels together.

Also, since some models only support modeling with numerical variables, processing categorical variables as WOE codes also provides more options for subsequent modeling.

Besides, considering the interpretability, WOE could be mapped to original values easily, while the WOE values themselves can reflect the relationship between each grouping and response variable. After coding, the model can still maintain good interpretability and will not affect the subsequent analysis.

Using the function build_woe below to apply WOE coding, while using get_woe_explain to save the mapping relationship of WOE coding and original value for the analysis later.

# WOE transformation
res_woe <- build_woe(diabetic_data, ycol = "readmitted",
                               positive = "YES", is_dropsame = TRUE)
#>  Creating woe binning ...
#>  Binning on 64359 rows and 30 columns in 00:00:02
#>  Converting into woe values ...
#>  Woe transformating on 64359 rows and 29 columns in 00:00:01
#> [1] "delete 1 constant columns"
diabetic_data_woe <- res_woe$newdata

# get the mapping information for explanation later.
tab_explain_woe <- get_woe_explain(diabetic_data_woe, diabetic_data)



2.3 Upsampling with SMOTE

Also check the response variable. It is an imbalanced classification as readmitted : non-readmitted :5$.

consider using SMOTE methods to do upsampling to balance the data.

SMOTE (Synthetic Minority Oversampling Technique) using KNNs idea to analyze the minority class and generate new samples to achieve an overall balance. following function would do upsampling with SMOTE and calculate the appropriate proportion needed for new cases generation automatically.

# codes for sample data to show the function which conduct SMOTE, it will be combined with the modelling function later
sample_smote <- upsample_smote(diabetic_data_woe[1:100, ], ycol = "readmitted")

summary(diabetic_data_woe[1:100, "readmitted"])
#>  NO YES 
#>  85  15
summary(sample_smote$readmitted)
#>  NO YES 
#>  85  75

Data becomes more balanced after SMOTE.



3. Analysis and Visualization

3.1 EDA and Visualization

firstly, try to check the relationship between the categorical variables and readmission. The following function plot_mosaic would give the mosaic plot for every variable in xcol v.s. ycol = readmitted

xcol <- c("race", "payer_code", "age", "insulin", "change", "max_glu_serum")
plot_mosaic(diabetic_ori, ycol = "readmitted", xcol = xcol, ncol = 3)

It shows that when age is increasing, the risk of readmission will drop first, then increase after 60 years old, which means that people at middle age has the relatively lower risk.

Also, based on race, some vulnerable groups such as Hispanic have lower rate of readmission surprisingly, that may because they cant afford the cost and time of repeated hospital admissions, or they are less concerned about their health and are reluctant to take treatment for a long time. This assumption may be supported by payer_code, which indicates how the patients pay during treatment. It also suggests that readmission is related to the different financial situation.

The medications during the admission and laboratory test results show significant relationship with the readmission. It shows that when there is a change in the dosage (up or down) of insulin, the risk of readmission increases. That may because it indicates the unstable disease development, which contributes to the readmission. This assumption is corresponding to the pattern showed bychange variable. However, the test result of glucose serum max_glu_serum shows when the value is high, it leads to significant higher risk of readmission, while A1C value A1C result dose not show significant difference.

Besides, check the relationship between the numerical variables and readmission. Similarly, the following function would give a histogram for each variable in xcol_num v.s. readmitted.

xcol_num <- c("time_in_hospital", "num_lab_procedures", "num_medications", 
              "number_inpatient", "number_diagnoses")
plot_comparehist(diabetic_ori, "readmitted", xcol_num, ncol = 2, bins = 10)

It shows that the number of hospital visiting, lab test and medications are related to readmission, which is intuitive that the patient who has the need and willing to take more check and receive more treatment is more likely to be readmitted. Also, when the patient has more diagnoses number_diagnoses, which means more other diseases at the same time, the situation could be worse. The number of inpatient visits of the patient number_inpatient is also an important indicator that it suggests a worse condition indirectly.


3.2 explaination with WOE

Moreover, give more exploration with the WOE coding results above.

On the one hand, as WOE combine different levels into different groups, the WOE value itself can be a measurement of the groups ability to identify readmitted patients: if there is no difference between the proportion within the groups and the proportion of the overall sample, then a WOE value is equal to \(\log{1} = 0\), indicating that this group may not related to readmission; similarly, when the WOE value is far from 0, it always indicates a stronger ability of the group for discrimination.

On the other hand, a positive or negative WOE can help to understand the tendency of patients in the group to be more or less likely to be readmitted: if the WOE value is negative, the group is less likely to be readmitted than the overall sample, vice versa.

based on the explanation table calculated by the functions above:

temp_col <- c("age", "number_diagnoses")
tab_explain_woe[tab_explain_woe$variable_name %in% temp_col, ]

It shows that the people at middle age is least likely to be readmitted (with the smallest value which is negative). As the age increasing, the risk of readmission is decreasing first, than increasing after 60, which denotes a non-linear relationship with readmission. But after transforming with WOE, the woe_value could be more linear to the readmission, when applying some linear model such as logistic regression, WOE coding could help the model to fit better.

Also, the number of diagnoses also shows significant relationship with readmission. Based on the WOE value, more diagnosed disease, the risk of being readmitted would increase. Also, as the woe_value is higher than the value of Age above (as 0.17 for number of diagnoses >= 9, while 0.1 for age >=70), it could be said that the number of diagnoses is a more important variable than age, which could provide more information about readmission.

Besides, as the number of diagnoses is a numeric variable here, it is divided into different bins by WOE. Similar to the idea of regression splines, it could also help model the non-linear relationship.

collist <- c("age", "number_diagnoses", "number_inpatient", "number_emergency")
get_woe_plot(res_woe$woe_bins, xcol = collist, ncol = 2)

4.1 Model with explainability: Logistic Regression

Firstly, fit a Logistic regression model with prepared data (with WOE coding)

The function below would work as : - split the data to train set and test set (set is_kfold to TRUE, and cv_num = 10 to do 10-fold validation. Refer to document for more information) - for each epoch in cross validation, do SMOTE sampling for the training data (if is_smote == TRUE) - fit the Logistic Regression model, learn the best threshold for classification by ROC information (calculated with specificity and sensitivity) - predict on the test data (with no SMOTE, to test the models ability about handling imbalance), set the threshold probability to different class with the best threshold learned above automatically - evaluate the result and give the result table

# build logistic model
res_logistic <- build_logistic_regression(diabetic_data_woe,
                      ycol = "readmitted", is_kfold = TRUE, cv_num = 10,
                      is_smote = TRUE, seed = 103221, auto_thre = TRUE)

get the evaluation result with 10-fold validation, also print the AUC plot:

res_logistic$eval_tab
plot(res_logistic$roc_res, print.auc=TRUE, auc.polygon=TRUE,
           grid.col=c("green", "red"), max.auc.polygon=TRUE,
           auc.polygon.col="skyblue", print.thres = T)

based on the result above with cross validation, AUC reaches 0.7 with recall about 0.65, which denotes that the simple logistic model fits data relatively well. Recall is a more important indicator here as wanting to ensure more patients with high risk of readmission could be found.

get the best threshold for classification (calculate automatically based on ROC):

res_logistic$best_thre

The patients with diagnosis as metabolic diseases or immunity disorders would have much higher risk for readmission than those who have digestive problems. The change in dosage of insulin also indicates higher probability of readmission, whether up or down. However, for metformin, lower doses and stopping are associated with readmission.



4.2 model for prediction: Random Forest

As the fitting ability of the Logistic regression is limited, try to use other methods for building the predictor.

Consider using the Random Forest model to construct the predictor, also with the SMOTE methods as tree-based models are sensitive to imbalance and calculating proper threshold automatically.

# build rf model
res_rf <- build_random_forest(diabetic_data_woe,
                      ycol = "readmitted", is_kfold = TRUE, cv_num = 10,
                      is_smote = TRUE, seed = 103221, 
                      ntree = 100, maxnodes = 50, mtry = 4)
res_rf$eval_tab

Random Forest model gets higher AUC around 0.87 that it could fit the target much better than Logistic Regression. While it gets much higher recall (0.74), which denotes that Random Forest could be more helpful for prediction in this case that missing readmitted patients is more costly.

Also, use random forest to give the importance of different variables.

impt <- res_rf$model$importance
impt <- impt[order(impt[, "MeanDecreaseGini"], decreasing = TRUE), ] |> 
  data.frame()
colnames(impt) <- c("MeanDecreaseGini")
impt

The result by random forest is corresponding to the visualization and analysis with logistic regression.

Moreover, noted that training a random forest model is quite slow, especially when the number of variables is large. Based on the WOE, try to do variables filter for a more concise model with IV (Information Value)

In this case, set the minimum IV value = 0.01 (iv_limit in following function)

# filter with iv
iv_res <- iv_filter(diabetic_data_woe, iv_limit = .01,
                        ycol = "readmitted", positive = 1)
#>  Filtering variables via info_value, missing_rate, identical_rate ...
#>  Variable filtering on 64359 rows and 28 columns in 00:00:03
#>  13 variables are removed
diabetic_data_iv <- iv_res$data_iv
iv_info <- iv_res$iv_info

dim(diabetic_data_iv)
#> [1] 64359    16

# get IV value for each variables: 
# print(iv_info)

get 15 explanatory variables left.

rebuild the model with data after filtering:

# build rf model
res_rf_iv <- build_random_forest(diabetic_data_iv,
                      ycol = "readmitted", is_kfold = TRUE, cv_num = 10,
                      is_smote = TRUE, seed = 103221, 
                      ntree = 100, maxnodes = 50, mtry = 4)
res_rf_iv$eval_tab

As there are only 15 explanatory variables left after filtering (compared with 29 before) the model is simplified with nearly half of them are removed. However, the model could still keep a relatively high AUC (from 0.868 before to 0.85 now) and even better performance in recall, and could be trained much faster. We could believe that filtering with IV is a good way for simplification.


4.2 demo: prediction for new data

Besides, this package also provides the following function model_predict as a simple way to use the trained model and do the prediction.

Use it to predict the 10 patients chosen randomly from the data, with the models trained above:


#### demo for building predictor for new data ####

# get 10 patients randomly for prediction
set.seed("2022620")
idx <- sample(1:dim(diabetic_data_woe)[1], 10)
true_label <- diabetic_data[idx, "readmitted"]
data <- diabetic_data_woe[idx,
                    -which(colnames(diabetic_data_woe) %in% c("readmitted"))]
lr_mod <- res_logistic$model
rf_mod <- res_rf$model
rf_mod_iv <- res_rf_iv$model

# do predict with functions below in BIS620.2022.final package:
pred_lr <- model_predict(data, res_logistic$model, 
                         thre = res_logistic$best_thre, 
                         classname = c("YES", "NO"))
pred_rf <- model_predict(data, res_rf$model, thre = res_rf$best_thre, 
                         classname = c("YES", "NO"))
pred_rf_iv <- model_predict(data, res_rf_iv$model, thre = res_rf_iv$best_thre, 
                         classname = c("YES", "NO"))

# show the result
predict_sample <- true_label |> data.frame()
predict_sample$pred_lr <- pred_lr
predict_sample$pred_rf <- pred_rf
predict_sample$pred_rf_iv <- pred_rf_iv
colnames(predict_sample) <- c("true label", 
                              "pred_Logistic", 
                              "pred_RF", 
                              "pred_RF+IV")

predict_sample
